  "text": "In terms of the mechanisms coupling the dysregulation of [Ca 2+ ] m to impaired maintenance and contractile function, we have two different leads. First, MICU1 loss has been shown to impair oxidative metabolism in hepatocytes and patient-derived cell lines, which has been attributed to ineffective activation of the Ca 2+ -sensitive dehydrogenases and other enzymes in the mitochondrial matrix due to less [Ca 2+ ] m rise during [Ca 2+ ] c spikes and oscillations [CITATION_1] . Consistent with this, we find that the MICU1-smKO mice show normal basal lactate levels, as observed in patients [CITATION_2] , but a greater rise upon exercise, which likely reflects the impaired adaptation of aerobic metabolism ( Figure 4I ). It seems plausible that dysregulation of the [Ca 2+ ] m -dependent steps of oxidative metabolism would be relevant for muscle fatigue and weakness in the MICU1-smKO mice.",
